{"key":"post-11579023","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11579023</id>\n<content>No to both.&amp;nbsp; I run one of those so-called HEPA units with paper filters in my living room all winter when the wood stove is heating our house.&amp;nbsp; It cuts down about 50% on the wood ash that settles as dust on our furniture and every thing else.&amp;nbsp; However, if it can only collect half of the relatively large dust particles, I wouldn't trust it to stop much of the bacteria and mold spores that will be in the air.&amp;nbsp; In fact it may stir them up.&amp;nbsp; A few years ago, I tried exactly what you're suggesting, by shutting it off before beginning sterile work.&amp;nbsp; My success was higher without ever running it in the first place.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're serious about the hobby and are going to be in it for awhile, pony up the cash for a laminar flow hood.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11579062</next>\n<prev>11579001</prev>\n<first>11578916</first>\n<last>11579101</last>\n<when>1259890778</when>\n<utime>12/04/09 03:39 AM</utime>\n</post>"}